    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-11-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-11-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="433"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d433">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2751.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <gloss type="from">Consul-General Iddings</gloss> to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Agency and Consulate-General</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-11-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 26, 1906</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Iddings informs Mr. Root that Nelken Waldberg, naturalized citizen of the
                    United States, District of Columbia, April, 1888, passport 70, Athens, April 7,
                    1904, publishes daily newspaper in Cairo, in which he attacks citizens and
                    members of the diplomatic corps; strong proof of blackmail is furnished and it
                    is desired by certain persons to expel Waldberg; states that it seems desirable
                    to silence Waldberg temporarily. Says his remonstrances are ineffective and
                    libel suits useless. Waldberg says he will apply for new passport. Requests
                    telegraphic instructions for immediate action.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
